The '''1906 WSPU march''' on 19 February 1906 was the first march held in London to demand the [[Women's suffrage in the United Kingdom|right to vote for women in  the United Kingdom]]. Organized by [[Sylvia Pankhurst]] and [[Annie Kenney]] of the [[Women's Social and Political Union]] (WSPU), the event saw around 300–400 women march through central London to the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]]. It was held to coincide with the King's Speech and the [[State Opening of Parliament|opening of Parliament]].{{sfn|Purvis|2002|p=79}} 

Two hundred women from [[Bow, London|Bow]], [[Bromley]], [[Canning Town]] and [[Poplar, London|Poplar]] in the East End marched to [[Caxton Hall]], near the Commons, from [[St. James's Park tube station]].{{sfn|Kelly|2004|p=333}} There, [[Emmeline Pankhurst]] heard there was no mention of votes for women in the King's Speech and led the women on another march to the Commons [[Strangers (Parliament of the United Kingdom)|Strangers' Entrance]]. Over the following two hours, the women were allowed to enter in groups of 20 to lobby their MPs.<ref>{{harvnb|Kelly|2004|p=334}}; {{harvnb|Van Wingerden|1999|p=75}}.</ref> The ''[[Daily Mirror]]'' reported the event on page 5: "Voteless Women. 3,000 [sic] Demonstrators March Behind a Red Banner. Smiling but Earnest."{{sfn|Kelly|2004|p=334}}

Emmeline Pankhurst saw the march as the beginning of a militant women's suffrage movement.{{sfn|Van Wingerden|1999|p=75}} The women "were awake at last", she wrote. "They were prepared to do something that women had never done before—fight for themselves. Women had always fought for men, and for their children. Now they were ready to fight for their own human rights. Our militant movement was established."{{sfn|Pankhurst|1914|p=38}}

