'''Chhetri''' ('''Kshetri''', '''Kshettri''', '''Kshetry''' or '''Chhettri'''), ({{lang-ne|क्षेत्री}}; [[IAST]]: ''Kṣetrī'') historically called '''Kshettriya''' or '''Kshetriya''', are [[Nepali language|Nepali]] speakers of [[Khas people|Khas]] community.{{sfn|Lawoti|2005|p=91}}<ref name=PON>{{cite book|title=People of Nepal|first=Dor Bahadur |last=Bista |authorlink=Dor Bahadur Bista |edition=4 |publisher=Ratna Pustak Bhandar |year=1980 |pages=2–4 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NiIKAQAAIAAJ}}</ref> Chhetri was a caste of administrators, governor and military elites in medieval [[Khasa kingdom|Khas Kingdom]] and [[Gorkha Kingdom]] (later unified [[Kingdom of Nepal]]).{{sfn|Pradhan|2012|pp=20-21}} The nobility of [[Gorkha Kingdom]] were mainly based from Chhetri families and they had a strong presence in civil administration affairs.{{sfn|Pahari|1995|p=632}} The bulk of [[Prime Minister of Nepal|Prime Ministers of Nepal]] before [[Revolution of 1951|democratization of Nepal]] belonged to this caste as a result of old Gorkhali aristocracy. Gorkha-based aristocratic Chhetri families were [[Pande dynasty]], [[Basnyat dynasty]], [[Thapa dynasty]] and Kunwars ([[Rana dynasty]] & other Kunwars).

Khas Chhetris (referred as '''Khas Rajputs'''{{sfn|Hitchcock|1978|p=116}}) were traditionally considered a division of the Khas people with [[Khas Brahmin]] (commonly called Khas Bahun).{{sfn|Hitchcock|1978|pp=116-119}} They make up 16.6% of Nepal's population according to the [[2011 Nepal census]], making them the most populous caste or [[ethnic groups in Nepal|ethnic community in Nepal]].<ref name="cbs"/> Chhetris speak an [[Indo-Aryan language|Indo-Aryan]] [[Nepali language]] (''[[Khas language|Khas-Kura]]'') as mother tongue.{{sfn|Dhungel|1998|p=5}}{{sfn|Lawoti|2005|p=91}} 
==Etymology & Background==
Chhetri is considered a direct derivative of the Sanskrit word ''[[Kshatriya]]''.{{sfn|Burghart|1984|p=119}}{{sfn|Gurung|1996|p=33}} According to the 1854 Legal Code (''Muluki Ain'') of Nepal, Chhetris are the social group among the [[Upanayana|sacred thread bearers]] (''Tagadhari'') and ''[[Dvija|twice-born people]]'' of the [[Hindu]] tradition.{{sfn|Sherchan|2001|p=14}}<ref>Gurung, H. (2005). Social exclusion and Maoist insurgency. Paper presented at National Dialogue Conference on ILO Convention 169 on Indigenous and Tribal Peoples, Kathmandu, 19–20 January 2005.</ref> Almost all Chhetris are Hindu.{{sfn|Dhungel|1998|p=8}} 

==History==
[[File:Bamshidhar Kalu Pande.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Kalu Pande]] wearing [[Khukuri]], a [[Pande family|Pande Chhetri]] aristocrat; [[Kaji (Nepal)|Kaji]] (Prime Minister and Army Chief) of [[Gorkha Kingdom]].]]
They are thought to be connected to the [[Khasas]] mentioned in the ancient Indian literature and the medieval [[Khasa kingdom]].<ref name="Pradhan1984">{{cite book |author=Kumar Pradhan |title=A History of Nepali Literature |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OdRjAAAAMAAJ |year=1984 |publisher=Sahitya Akademi |page=5 }}</ref>

In the early modern history of Nepal, Chhetris played a key role in the [[Unification of Nepal]], providing the core of the [[Gurkha|Gorkhali]] army of the mid-18th century.<ref name=Faces/> [[Bir Bhadra Thapa]] was a [[Thapa]] of Chhetri group{{sfn|Regmi|1995|p=44}} and leading Bharadar during [[Unification of Nepal]].{{sfn|Pradhan|2012|p=22}} His grandson [[Bhimsen Thapa]] became [[List of Prime Ministers of Nepal|Mukhtiyar (Prime Minister) of Nepal]].{{sfn|Pradhan|2012|p=22}} [[Swarup Singh Karki]], a leading politician and military officer, belonged to Chhetri family.{{sfn|Singh|1997|p=142}} [[Abhiman Singh Basnyat]] of [[Basnyat dynasty]] and [[Damodar Pande]] of [[Pande dynasty]] were both members of Chhetri caste.{{sfn|Regmi|1975|p=73}} [[Jung Bahadur Rana]], founder of [[Rana dynasty]] also belonged to the Chhetri community.{{sfn|Adhikari|2015|p=120}}

[[File:Bhimsen Thapa of Nepal (cropped).jpg|upright|thumb|[[Bhimsen Thapa]], a leading Chhetri [[Mukhtiyar]] (Prime Minister).]]
During the monarchy, Chhetris continued to dominate the ranks of the [[Government of Nepal|Nepalese government]], [[Nepalese Army]], [[Nepal Police|Nepalese Police]] and administration.<ref name=Faces>{{cite book|title=Faces of Nepal |first=Harka B. |last=Gurung |publisher=Himal Books |year=1996 |pages=1–33, ''passim'' |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9tSBAAAAMAAJ}}</ref>

===Chhetri noble families===
[[File:Abhiman Singh Basnyat.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Abhiman Singh Basnyat]], a [[Basnyat family|Basnyat Kshetri]] [[Mulkaji]] (Prime Minister)]]
The most prominent feature of Nepalese Chhetri society has been the ruling [[Shah dynasty]] (1768–2008){{refn|group=note|Shah monarchs were placed among [[Thakuri]] caste instead of Chhetri.{{sfn|Pahari|1995|p=631}}}}, the [[Rana dynasty|Rana Prime Ministers]] (1846–1953), [[Pande family]], [[Thapa family]], [[Basnyat family]],{{sfn|Pahari|1995|p=632}}. that marginalized the monarchy, and the Chhetri presence in the armed forces, police, and [[Government of Nepal]]. In traditional and administrative professions, Chhetris were given favorable treatment by the [[Kingdom of Nepal|royal government]].<ref name=Burbank>{{cite book|title=Nepal |series=Cultures of the World |first=Jon |last=Burbank |edition=2 |publisher=Marshall Cavendish |year=2002 |isbn=0-7614-1476-2 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EaWLU6Blh_sC}}</ref><ref name=CHN>{{cite book|title=Cultural History of Nepal |first1=Bhadra Ratha |last1=Bajracharya |first2=Shri Ram |last2=Sharma |first3=Shiri Ram |last3=Bakshi |publisher=Anmol Publications |year=1993 |isbn=81-7041-840-2 |pages=286–8 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lELMFa9yZqsC}}</ref>

===Chhetri and premiership===
The nobility of [[Gorkha Kingdom|Gorkha]] were mainly from Chhetri families and they had a strong presence in civil administration affairs.{{sfn|Pahari|1995|p=632}} All of the [[Prime Minister of Nepal]] between 1768 to 1950 were Chhetris with the exception of [[Ranga Nath Poudyal]], being a Brahmin.{{sfn|Raj|1996|p=5}} These number varied after the [[Revolution of 1951|democratization of Nepal]]. Between 1951 to 1997, out of the 16 Prime Ministers of Nepal, 5 of them were Chhetris.{{sfn|Gurung|1998|p=129}}

==Military achievements==
[[File:Bir Shamsher JBR.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Bir Shamsher JBR]], a [[Rana family|Rana Kshetri]] [[Maharaja]], and Prime Minister and C-in-C of Nepal]]
Chhetri had dominated high military positions and monopolized the military force at the times of Chhetri autocratic administrators like PM [[Bhimsen Thapa]] and PM [[Jung Bahadur Rana]]. There were 12 [[Basnyat family|Basnyat]]s, 16 [[Pande family|Pande]]s, 6 [[Thapa family|Thapa]]s and 3 [[Rana dynasty|Kunwar]] officers totalling to 51 Chhetri officers in the year 1841&nbsp; A.D.{{sfn|Adhikari|2015|p=120}} The most prominent officers at [[Shah dynasty|Shah administration]] were the [[Kaji (Nepal)|Kazis]] which had control over civil and military functions like a Minister and Military officer combined. [[Rana Jang Pande]], the leader of Pande faction, was the [[List of Prime Ministers of Nepal|Prime Minister of Nepal]] in 1841&nbsp; A.D.{{sfn|Joshi|Rose|1966|p=27}} which might have caused large Pande officers at 1841. After the rise [[Rana dynasty]](Kunwars), the number changed to 10 [[Basnyat family|Basnyat]]s, 1 [[Pande family|Pande]]s, 3 [[Thapa family|Thapa]]s and 26 [[Rana dynasty|Kunwar]] officers totaling to 61 Chhetri officers in the year 1854&nbsp; A.D.{{sfn|Adhikari|2015|p=120}}

Chhetris dominated the position of the senior officers of the Nepali Army comprising 74.4% of total senior officers in 1967. Similarly, Chhetris composed of 38.1%, 54.3% and 55.3% of the senior officers in the year 2003, 2004 and 2007 respectively.{{sfn|Adhikari|2015|p=123}}
