==Demographics==
The 2011 Nepal census recorded Chhetris as the largest [[Hinduism in Nepal|Hindu]] adherents in the nation with 43,65,113 people which is 99.3% of total Chhetri population.<ref name="cbs"/> Those Chhetri who follow Hinduism may also follow Buddhism. The ancient religion of the Chhetri is Masto which uses nature worship and can still be seen in western Nepal's Karnali district and in India's [[Gorkhaland]]. In Nepal's hill districts the Chhetri population rises to 41% compared to 31% [[Brahmin]] and 27% other castes. This greatly exceeds the Kshatriya portion in most regions with predominantly Hindu populations.<ref name=CBS1>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbs.gov.np/Population/Monograph/Chapter%2003%20%20Social%20Composition%20of%20the%20Population.pdf |title=Chapter 3. Social composition of the Population: Caste/Ethnicity and Religion in Nepal |first=Dilli Ram |last=Dahal |publisher=[[Government of Nepal]], Central Bureau of Statistics |date=2002-12-30 |accessdate=2011-04-02 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110519235652/http://www.cbs.gov.np/Population/Monograph/Chapter%2003%20%20Social%20Composition%20of%20the%20Population.pdf |archivedate=2011-05-19}}</ref><ref name=CBS2>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbs.gov.np/Nepal%20in%20figure/Nepal%20in%20Figures%202008.pdf |title=Nepal in Figures 2008 |format=PDF |publisher=[[Government of Nepal]], Central Bureau of Statistics |year=2008 |accessdate=2011-04-03 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110723080755/http://www.cbs.gov.np/Nepal%20in%20figure/Nepal%20in%20Figures%202008.pdf |archivedate=2011-07-23}}</ref>

Chhetris are largest caste group in 21 [[districts of Nepal]] as per [[2001 Nepal census]] and 24 districts as per [[2011 Nepal census]]. These twenty four districts are - [[Dhankuta district]], [[Sankhuwasabha district]], [[Okhaldhunga district]], [[Udayapur district]], [[Ramechhap district]], [[Dolakha District]], [[Salyan District, Nepal|Salyan district]], [[Surkhet district]], [[Dailekh district]], [[Jajarkot district]], [[Dolpa district]], [[Jumla district]], [[Mugu district]], [[Humla district]], [[Bajura district]], [[Bajhang district]], [[Achham district]], [[Doti district]], [[Kailali district]], [[Dadeldhura district]], [[Baitadi district]], [[Darchula district]], [[Kalikot district]] and [[Kanchanpur district]].<ref name="cbs"/> Among them, the district with largest Chhetri population is [[Kathmandu district]] with 347,754 (i.e. 19.9% of the total district population).<ref name="cbs"/> The literacy rate among Chhetris is 72.3% as per [[2011 Nepal census]].<ref name="cbs"/> 

As per the [[Public Service Commission (Nepal)|Public Service Commission]] of Nepal, [[Bahun|Brahmins]] (33.3%) and Chhetris (20.01%) were two largest caste group to obtain governmental jobs in the fiscal year 2017-18 even though 45% governmental seats are reserved for women, indigenous groups, [[Madhesi people|Madhesis]], [[Dalit]]s, people with disability and those from the backward regions.<ref>http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/news/2018-10-16/brahmins-and-chhetris-land-most-government-jobs.html</ref>

==Present day==
[[File:Small Thapa family.jpg|thumb|A 21st century Chhetri family]]
Chhetri together with Bahun and thakuri  falls under [[Khas Arya]], who are denied [[Racial quota|quota]] and reservations in civil services and other sectors due to their history of socio-political dominance in Nepal.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/khas-arya-quota-provision-civil-services-opposed/|title=Khas Arya quota provision in civil services opposed|author=|date=10 November 2017|website=thehimalayantimes.com|accessdate=1 May 2018}}</ref> There are no quotas for the [[Khas community]] who fall under ''Bahun-Chhetri-thakuri'' hierarchy.<ref>{{Cite news|first=Trailokya Raj|last=Aryal|URL=http://www.myrepublica.com/news/20612/|title= The Bahun narrative|date=24 May 2017|newspaper= [[República (Nepalese newspaper)|Myrepublica]]|access-date=25 January 2018}}</ref> As per the explanation of legal provisions of [[Constitution of Nepal]], Khas Arya comprises the Brahmin, Kshetri, Thakur and Sanyasi (Dashnami) communities.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mainstreamweekly.net/article7834.html|title=Nepal-India Relations: Need for Urgent Paradigm Shift - Mainstream Weekly|author=|date=|website=www.mainstreamweekly.net|accessdate=8 June 2018}}</ref> But they are allowed reservation in federal parliament and provincial legislature.<ref name="article5111223">{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/opinion/columns/next-door-nepal-the-nationalists-hour-5111223/|title=Next Door Nepal: The nationalist’s hour|author=|date=26 March 2018|website=indianexpress.com|accessdate=8 June 2018}}</ref> The [[European Union]] has been accused of direct interference, creating ethnic strife and negative discrimination towards ''Khas Arya'' due to their recommendation to remove the reservation for Khas Aryas.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nepalitimes.com/here-now/hail-to-the-chiefs/|title=Hail to the chiefs|first=Om Astha|last=Rai|date=|website=www.nepalitimes.com|accessdate=8 June 2018}}</ref><ref name="article5111223"/>

